y and of post-socialist economic reforms. However, they are also sites of great contestation, sparking land disputes and controversies over how to compensate evicted residents. In this penetrating ethnography, Erik Harms vividly portrays the human costs of urban reorganization as he explores the complex and sometimes contradictory experiences of individuals grappling with the forces of privatization in a socialist country.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066754740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520966017?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966017zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966017/original  a978-3-11-064982-6 Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066754-7 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA